================================================================================
  ASSEMBLER  (asm.cpp)
================================================================================

  The assembler is two-pass and reads the source file exactly once. All lines
  are stored in a vector of meta_data structs during that first read. Pass 2
  iterates over the stored vector - no second file read is done.

  Both passes share a single loop body, switched by a parse flag (1 or 2).
  Pass 1 collects label names and their PC values into Label_Table without
  failing on undefined references. Pass 2 resolves everything and encodes
  each instruction.

  Instruction lookup goes through a static table ins_type[] with 21 entries
  covering all 19 real SIMPLEX instructions and the two pseudo-instructions
  (data, SET). Each entry holds the mnemonic, opcode, operand flag, branch
  flag, and pseudo flag. No instruction behaviour is hard-coded outside it.

  Numbers are parsed with strtol(s, &end, 0) which handles decimal, hex
  (0x prefix) and octal (leading 0) automatically. The end pointer check
  catches trailing garbage that strtol would otherwise silently ignore.


  Program flow  (asm.cpp)
  ------------------------

  main()
  |
  +-- remove_comment()
  |
  +-- [PASS 1]
  |     +-- is_a_label()
  |     |     +-- rewrite_label()
  |     +-- hex_counter()
  |
  +-- [PASS 2]
  |     +-- break_parts()
  |     +-- decode_instruction()
  |           +-- find_instruction()
  |           +-- convert_opcode()
  |           +-- convert_immedt()
  |                 +-- convert_value()
  |                 +-- convert_offset()
  |                       +-- convert_value()  
  |
  +-- write_obj_file()
  +-- write_lst_file()
  |     +-- print_to_file()
  +-- write_log_file()
        +-- print_to_file()

  function              description
  --------------------  ---------------------------------------------------------
  main                  drives the two-pass loop, calls output writers at the end
  remove_comment        strips ; comments and collapses extra whitespace
  is_a_label            validates label syntax and inserts it into Label_Table
  rewrite_label         called for SET only - overwrites label value with constant
  hex_counter           increments the hex PC string after each emitted line
  break_parts           splits a line into mnemonic + operand tokens
  find_instruction      searches ins_type[] for the mnemonic, null if not found
  decode_instruction    top-level encoder, builds the full 8 hex char word
  convert_opcode        converts integer opcode to 2 hex chars for the low byte
  convert_immedt        checks operand count and routes to value or offset encoder
  convert_value         encodes a number or label ref to 6 hex chars with overflow check
  convert_offset        computes branch displacement then calls convert_value
  write_obj_file        writes 4 bytes LSB-first per word into the binary .obj
  write_lst_file        writes address + hex word + source text for every line
  write_log_file        same as lst but appends an error message on flagged lines
  print_to_file         shared formatter called by both lst and log writers


  Encoding
  --------
  Every word is 32 bits:

        [  bits 31 .. 8  ]  [  bits 7 .. 0  ]
           24-bit operand       8-bit opcode

  Branch offsets use:   displacement = target_address - current_PC - 1
  because the PC is incremented before the branch displacement is applied.


  Pseudo-instruction encoding  (data and SET)
  --------------------------------------------
  => data is assigned opcode 0xFF. The 24-bit operand field stores the value.
     Because the opcode byte consumes 8 of the 32 bits, only 24 bits are left
     for the actual constant in one word. A full 32-bit value cannot fit in a
     single data line and would need to be split or built at runtime with
     ldc + adc.

  => SET is assigned opcode 0xFE. It is assembler-time only - it rewrites the
     label's entry in Label_Table to a fixed constant instead of the current
     PC, emits nothing into the object file, and does not advance PC.

  The 0xFF and 0xFE markers exist so the emulator can identify these slots
  when reading memory and handle them differently from real instructions.


  Label handling and edge cases
  ------------------------------
  => Duplicate labels : the FIRST occurrence is kept as the valid definition.
     The second triggers error -2 but all references still resolve to the
     first. Subsequent duplicates are each flagged individually.

  => A label name that matches any instruction mnemonic (e.g. "add:", "br:")
     is rejected with error -1.

  => Labels must start with a letter and contain only alphanumeric characters.
     Starting with a digit or using a hyphen etc. gives error -3.

  => A label alone on a line with nothing after the colon is warning -4.
     No machine code is produced and PC does not advance for that line.

  => A space before the colon  (e.g. "myLabel :")  is not recognised as a
     label. The line falls through to mnemonic parsing and will usually error.

  => SET without a label in front of it is error -10. There is no symbol to
     bind the value to so the directive is meaningless.

  => Unlabeled data is warning -11. The word is still emitted into the object
     file (it occupies memory) but can never be referenced by name.


  Error and warning codes
  -----------------------
     -1    label name collides with a mnemonic
     -2    duplicate label  (first occurrence kept)
     -3    invalid label name
     -4    empty label  [warning]
     -5    unknown mnemonic
     -6    too many operands or operand not expected
     -8    undefined label / operand is neither a number nor a known label
     -9    missing operand
    -10    SET with no label
    -11    unlabeled data  [warning]
    -12    positive overflow  (exceeds 24-bit max  0xFFFFFF / 16777215)
    -13    negative overflow  (below 24-bit min  -8388608)

  => All errors across the entire file are reported in one pass. The assembler
     never aborts at the first error.

  => The .obj file is always produced — it contains valid encodings only and
     may be empty if no line in the file assembled cleanly.

  => The .log file is only produced when errors exist. A clean source file
     generates no log.


  Output files
  ------------
  .obj  =>  binary, little-endian 32-bit words starting at address 0.
            Each 8-hex-digit code is written as 4 bytes LSB first.
            Always produced — contains valid encodings only, may be empty.

  .lst  =>  text listing with address, encoded word, and original source
            for every line. Pseudo-instruction words are shown with a
            "00" prefix to distinguish them visually.

  .log  =>  mirrors the listing and appends an error message after each
            line that has a non-zero error code. Only written when errors
            exist.


