================================================================================
  EMULATOR  (emu.cpp)
================================================================================

  The emulator loads the .obj binary into a flat byte vector. An extra 100000
  bytes are appended above the program to give the stack space to grow. The
  loaded program size is saved as s (in words) for use during execution.

  Registers at startup:  A=0, B=0, PC=0, SP=0x270F.

  All 19 real SIMPLEX instructions are implemented:
    ldc  adc  ldl  stl  ldnl  stnl  add  sub  shl  shr
    adj  a2sp  sp2a  call  return  brz  brlz  br  HALT


  Program flow  (emu.cpp)
  ------------------------

  main()
  |
  +-- setup_output_files()
  +-- load_program()
  +-- start_execution()
        |
        +-- print_table_header()
        +-- print_bfrafr_header()
        +-- get_word()
        +-- process_instr()
              +-- get_decoded()
              +-- write_to_files()
              +-- build_row()
              +-- build_bfrafr_row()
              +-- set_word()
              +-- write_result()

  function              description
  --------------------  ---------------------------------------------------------
  main                  parses flags, rejects unknown args, kicks off execution
  setup_output_files    opens .trace / .bfrafr / .memdump based on active flags
  load_program          reads .obj into memory vector, sets s and SP
  start_execution       fetch-decode-execute loop, runs until HALT or error
  print_table_header    writes column labels at the top of the trace output
  print_bfrafr_header   writes column labels at the top of the bfrafr output
  get_word              bounds check + sign-extends 0xFF data words below s
  process_instr         snapshots regs, runs opcode switch, writes output rows
  get_decoded           disassembles a raw word into a printable mnemonic string
  write_to_files        sends a string to stdout and .trace file simultaneously
  build_row             formats one trace row  (count | hex | mnemonic | PC | A | B | SP)
  build_bfrafr_row      formats one before/after register state row
  set_word              bounds check then writes 4 bytes into the memory vector
  write_result          dumps memdump at HALT and closes all open output files


  get_word - how memory reads work
  ---------------------------------
  => For addresses inside the program region (word address < s), the lowest
     byte is checked. If it equals 0xFF the word is a data slot. The upper
     24 bits are sign-extended to a full 32-bit signed value before returning:

         int32_t signed_val = (int32_t)val >> 8;
         return (uint32_t)signed_val;

     This correctly recovers the original constant including negative values
     that were packed as 24-bit two's complement by the assembler.

  => For addresses at or above s (stack and runtime data area), the raw
     32-bit value is returned as-is. Sign extension does not apply there
     since nothing enforces the 0xFF encoding in that region.

  => Any access where  address * 4 + 3 >= memory.size()  prints an error
     and exits immediately.


  Runtime errors detected
  -----------------------
  => PC out of bounds           checked before every instruction fetch
  => memory read out of bounds  checked inside get_word
  => memory write out of bounds checked inside set_word
  => unknown opcode             default case prints the opcode and exits


  Output flags
  ------------
  -trace    =>  per-instruction table: count | hex word | mnemonic | PC | A | B | SP
  -bfrafr   =>  register state immediately before and after each instruction
  -memdump  =>  first 10000 word addresses dumped as hex pairs at HALT

  The built-in disassembler (get_decoded) sign-extends the 24-bit operand
  before printing, so negative branch offsets show as negative numbers.


================================================================================
  ASSUMPTIONS AND KNOWN LIMITATIONS
================================================================================

  1.  Written in C++11 not C89. Logic and design follow the spec guidance;
      only the standard library containers differ from C-style arrays.
 
  2.  data can only hold a 24-bit value per word. The 0xFF opcode occupies
      the lower 8 bits so there is no room for a full 32-bit constant in one
      data directive.
 
  3.  Duplicate labels - first definition wins, subsequent ones are errors.
 
  4.  shr is a logical (unsigned) right shift, not arithmetic.
 
  5.  Label names are case-sensitive. "Loop" and "loop" are distinct.
 
  6.  HALT does not increment instr_count. The counter in the trace reflects
      only the instructions executed before HALT, not HALT itself.
 
  7.  SP is hardcoded to 0x270F (chosen arbitrarily) at startup. Programs that
      use stack instructions without first calling a2sp will silently read and 
      write at whatever that address maps to. Behaviour in that case is undefined.
 
  8.  memdump always covers exactly 1000000 word addresses regardless of how
      much the program actually used. The rest reads back as 0x00000000.
 
  9.  Memory is zero-initialised. A program cannot distinguish between an
      address that was never written and one explicitly set to zero.
 
  10. It is assumed that an infinite loop was intentionally coded.
      so an infinite loop does what its supposed to do: run infinitely
      No infinite loop detection. A program that never reaches HALT will
      run forever — there is no instruction limit or timeout guard.


